# Stream: live ingestion into the zettelkasten

This rule explains how to use **Stream** -- the capability that turns a live feed
of documents into grounded zettelkasten notes by driving a coordinator graph with
a portable agent backend. It fires when the user wants to ingest a stream of
documents (earnings reports, filings, papers, letters, product pages) on a
schedule or on demand, extract them under one or more schemas, and analyze the
result per project.

Stream is general-purpose. Earnings reports are the first worked recipe, not the
only use. It builds on the grounded-extraction pipeline (extractor -> scribe ->
auditor) and the schema registry, so the zettelkasten capability must be enabled.

## Portability (no Cursor required)

The core path has no Cursor dependency. Agents run through a portable `Driver`:

- `claude` -- Anthropic API (set `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`). Default.
- `gpt` -- OpenAI-compatible API (set `OPENAI_API_KEY`), or a local/open-weight
  model via `base_url` (e.g. a vLLM server -- also the reference setup for
  logprob-based confidence).
- `cursor` -- optional plugin for running inside Cursor (not needed otherwise).

Install the SDK(s) you use: `pip install "angelo[stream]"` (both), or just
`anthropic` / `openai`.

## Two ways to run

### Programmatic

```python
import stream

# One batch, in hand:
report = stream.apply(
    ["./inbox/AAPL-10Q.pdf"],
    project="aapl",
    schemas=["earnings"],     # one or more global schemas
    driver="claude",          # or "gpt", optionally model=..., base_url=...
)

# Build a comparison matrix and export CSV (deterministic, no LLM):
stream.export_csv("aapl", "aapl.csv", schema="earnings")

# Or synthesize a grounded narrative with an agent:
out = stream.synthesize_narrative("aapl", schema="earnings",
                                  driver=stream.make_driver("claude"),
                                  write_back=True)  # writes a _cross synthesis note
```

`apply()` = `prepare()` (build + register the coordinator graph) + `run()` (drive
it to completion with the Driver). Multi-schema: one extraction pass over the
sources, one synthesis spine per schema; each claim attaches to every relevant
spine.

### Config-driven (always-on)

Drop a `stream.yaml` at the project root, then:

```bash
angelo-stream --once                 # single pass over the feeds
angelo-stream --config stream.yaml   # daemon: poll + ingest forever
```

The daemon polls each feed, selects schema(s) per document, routes to project(s),
applies, then archives + (optionally) deletes the originals.

## Starter stream.yaml

```yaml
defaults:
  driver: claude            # claude | gpt | cursor
  model: ""                 # optional model override
  base_url: ""              # for gpt against a local/OpenAI-compatible endpoint
  concurrency: 2            # parallel agents per wave
  rigor: medium             # low | medium | high (extension cycles + passes)
  template: extraction      # workflow template (built-in: extraction)
  project: research         # fallback project when routing yields none
  score_driver: ""          # advisory confidence pass; "" disables. logprob-
                            # capable backend (e.g. gpt against a vLLM endpoint)
  score_model: ""           # model for the scorer (e.g. an open-weight model)
  score_base_url: ""        # OpenAI-compatible endpoint for the scorer (vLLM)

archive: local              # none | local | dvc  (what to keep of the original
                            # binary before the feed deletes it)

feeds:
  - name: inbox
    type: drop_dir          # built-in; custom feeds via entry points
    options:
      path: ./inbox
      glob: "*.pdf"
      delete_after: true    # remove the file once its run succeeds

schemas:                    # document -> schema name(s) (UNION)
  default: []               # applied when no rule matches ([] = semantic only)
  rules:
    - match: {doc_type: pdf}
      schemas: [earnings]
  # classifier: my_classifier   # optional entry-point fallback

router:                     # document -> project name(s) (orthogonal to schemas)
  default: [research]
  axes:
    - type: metadata
      key: ticker           # one project per distinct ticker value
      # template: "{value}"  # or map: {AAPL: apple, MSFT: microsoft}
```

Schemas are GLOBAL organizing lenses; projects are read-time SCOPES. A document
can be extracted under several schemas and routed to several projects.

## Customizing (Python entry points)

Register plugins in your `pyproject.toml`:

- `angelo.stream.feeds` -- `name = module:factory(FeedConfig) -> FeedAdapter`
  (e.g. an API poller, a Snowflake/warehouse query, a webhook sink).
- `angelo.stream.routers` -- custom project routing.
- `angelo.stream.selectors` -- `name = module:fn(Document) -> list[str]` schema
  classifier fallback.
- `angelo.stream.templates` -- a custom `WorkflowTemplate` building an arbitrary
  coordinator graph.

Custom agent types use the normal coordinator mechanism (`.cursor/agents.yaml`).
Reinstall (`pip install -e .`) after adding entry points so they're discovered.

## New-repo setup

1. `pip install "angelo[stream]"` and `angelo init --with-zettelkasten`.
2. Set the provider key (`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` or `OPENAI_API_KEY`).
3. Define or pick a schema (see the grounded-extraction rule + the schema
   registry). Schemas live globally; projects filter at read time.
4. Write `stream.yaml` (above), create `./inbox`, drop a document in.
5. `angelo-stream --once` to process, then inspect the project in the
   zettelkasten dashboard or export a matrix with `stream.export_csv(...)`.

## Notes

- Confidence (logprobs) is ADVISORY under auto-publish: recorded/flagged, never a
  gate. Set `score_driver` (+ `score_model`/`score_base_url`) to a logprob-capable
  `gpt` backend (e.g. vLLM) and a post-extraction pass scores each claim against
  its evidence, persisting the result onto the note's grounding. It then surfaces
  in the dashboard note panel and the synthesis-matrix cells (low-confidence cells
  are flagged). Without a logprob backend the pass degrades gracefully (no score
  persisted) and the run still publishes.
- "Distill and discard": with a schema + `archive`/`delete_after`, you can take
  grounded notes off a stream and drop the originals -- the notes stay
  self-contained and quote-grounded.
